{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"79478a5ae6e4ab15edf597fec5626c05a9f3949cb94b260af631c830ccd043cb","slug":"medium-mixtures","location":"/explanation/medium_mixtures.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Medium Mixtures","content_includes_title":false,"github":"https://github.com/open223/docs.open223.info","numbering":{"title":{"offset":1}},"source_url":"https://github.com/open223/docs.open223.info/blob/main/explanation/medium_mixtures.md","edit_url":"https://github.com/open223/docs.open223.info/edit/main/explanation/medium_mixtures.md","thumbnail":"/build/mixed_medium-5195d8a764f5058c5e17631facac8ede.png","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"medium_mixtures.md","url":"/build/medium_mixtures-28556ad1c68595978a34be562d09f10a.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The 223 standard includes a large set of enumerations, defined as a hierarchy of subclasses under the class ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"YCaZrVw31p"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:EnumerationKind","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"frSoiuJqPN"},{"type":"text","value":".\nOne important piece of this hierarchy is the class ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"nmb3mIGgaD"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:EnumerationKind-Substance","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"l79Vq7c2fG"},{"type":"text","value":" and its direct subclass ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"NDewSpWcKS"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:Substance-Medium","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"Fom87bwdfi"},{"type":"text","value":".\nIt is this branch of the hierarchy where you can find what you would expect to be flowing in a building, such as water, air and electricity. It is important to understand how a medium is modeled, especially when that medium is a mixture. The diagram below sketches the structure of the hierarchy. The names of the classes are abbreviated for clarity, so ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"aPp0xKfmEf"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:Substance-Medium","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"CPtP8sAFHU"},{"type":"text","value":" is shown as Medium for example. In the standard, each of the names follows the hyphenated naming convention of <parent class>-<local class>.","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"uWmJJYT5lz"}],"key":"bmGXGjp5BD"},{"type":"image","url":"/build/mixed_medium-5195d8a764f5058c5e17631facac8ede.png","alt":"MixedMedium","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"Ae3ayCMjib","urlSource":"images/mixed_medium.png"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note in the figure that there is a division of the Medium class into Mix and Constituent. The Mix class is further divided into Fluid and Power&Signal. Fluid means what you might think - a liquid or gas that typically flows inside some sort of conduit like a duct or a pipe. You can find Water and Air here. To capture the description of what is in a mixture, the model contains the class Constituent and its subclasses. These subclasses are intended to identify the constituents of a mixture. So, for example, a water-glycol mixture would be defined as ","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"i5uKiR57oe"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:Water-GlycolSolution","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"HckBGXxEeg"},{"type":"text","value":", with two Properties via the relation ","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"wjJdcVpnWs"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:composedOf","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"b7x9AHVGx1"},{"type":"text","value":". Each of these Properties has a relation ","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"VAKjtrlESI"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:ofConstituent","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"enkuuvVmk4"},{"type":"text","value":" that identifies one of the constituents from the Medium-Constituent hierarchy. Each Property also captures any other defining information. This is illustrated in the following figure for a 30%  Water-Glycol mixture.","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"Qi3NKk6RKT"}],"key":"IWTjfYGW9k"},{"type":"image","url":"/build/glycol_example-6c785d66fd3883cf81ca119c0efd64e4.png","alt":"GlycolExample","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"key":"nrBfGFnahk","urlSource":"images/glycol_example.png"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Mixtures (","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"PHDJ15unNM"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:Medium-Mix","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"tWaFH8F3lU"},{"type":"text","value":") and constituents (","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"qdqmqd2WD9"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"s223:Medium-Constituent","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"EvvuH2yBEe"},{"type":"text","value":") are modeled this way to allow for compatibility validation among ConnectionPoints and Connections. Two mediums are deemed compatible if they share at least one common constituent.","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"mZOmsk3EW6"}],"key":"pG15V11q3s"}],"key":"afsBPlE2eS"}],"key":"lkeHi0Ms7w"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"prev":{"title":"Heat Transfer Equipment","url":"/heat-transfer-equipment","group":"Explanation"},"next":{"title":"Sensors and Properties","url":"/sensors-and-properties","group":"Explanation"}}},"domain":"http://localhost:3000"}